{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504920"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:23:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2387"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.08,0.23,0.03,0.56]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84762"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2387"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69054"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"2207"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1533"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1539"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2260"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14367"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28783"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84762"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department, having been found by his wife wandering around the street in a confused state. He has a medical history of small cell lung cancer diagnosed a year ago as well as COPD, diabetes mellitus and hypertension. His regular medications include metformin, amlodipine, morphine liquid and several inhalers. He is under the care of an oncology team for his recent cancer diagnosis, in addition to a respiratory physician who manages his COPD. He has a 40-pack-year smoking history but stopped when he was diagnosed with lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 84/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, temperature is 37.2 \u00b0C, and respiration rate 16/min. He is disoriented to time and place. Ophthalmological examination shows papilloedema. Pupils are 2 mm in diameter in bright light. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. Laboratory results show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 118 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 24 mmol/L (20-32)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood glucose 15 mmol/L (3.6-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary ketones negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this patient\u0027s confusion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brain metastases","Hydrocephalus","Hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state","Opioid intoxication","Syndrome of inappropriate ADH"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThie most likely cause of this patient\u0027s confusion is their significant hyponatraemia - paired with a history of small cell lung carcinoma, he most likely has a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Esyndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion (SIADH).\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESIADH is a paraneoplastic syndrome associated with small cell lung carcinoma (Image). It is characterised by euvolaemic hyponatraemia. Patients may present either with nausea and fatigue with mild hyponatraemia, or altered mental status, elevated intracranial pressure, and coma with severe derangements in serum sodium levels. SIADH is associated with small cell lung carcinoma, medications (e.g. SSRIs), and CNS pathologies (e.g. stroke, trauma). The decision of the choice of management depends on the clinical features and the sodium levels in the serum. Patients with sodium levels \u0026gt;120 mmol/L and no CNS symptoms are recommended treatment with fluid restriction. On the other hand, patients with serum sodium \u0026lt;120 mmol/L or severe neurological signs and symptoms (eg, altered mental status, signs of elevated intracranial pressure) should be treated with hypertonic (3%) saline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrain metastasis \u003C/strong\u003Eis a reasonable differential in the patient with confusion and a known history of cancer. However, with no other neurological signs or symptoms, a brain lesion is less likely to be the primary cause of his altered mental status especially given the degree of hyponatraemia present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperosmolar hyperglycaemic\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Estates\u003C/strong\u003E also present with altered mental status and may cause a pseudohyponatraemia. However, an only mildly elevated blood sugar level and normal serum potassium are inconsistent with this differential, and a patient presenting with HHS would be expected to be dehydrated with some degree of derangement in vital signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocephalus\u003C/strong\u003E may be associated with altered mental status and papilloedema. However, hyponatraemia and a history of small cell lung cancer make the diagnosis of SIADH more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOpioid intoxication \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with altered mental status, respiratory depression, and miosis. This patient\u2019s normal respiratory rate and normal size of the pupil makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyponatraemia in the presence of carcinoma of the lung must raise the possibility of the syndrome of inappropriate ADH secretion."],"references":["Fiordoliva I, Meletani T, Baleani M, Rinaldi S, Savini A, Di Pietro Paolo M et al. Managing hyponatremia in lung cancer: latest evidence and clinical implications. Therapeutic Advances in Medical Oncology. 2017;9(11):711-719. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5764155/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69054"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17186"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17186"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f8bfb4ef-3028-4ad8-b06c-babe2d58abc8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f8bfb4ef-3028-4ad8-b06c-babe2d58abc8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":609,"height":143}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69054"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-10T18:25:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-10T18:25:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2387"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84762"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c","name":"Critical Care Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p